[
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1608.02664\">https://arxiv.org/abs/1608.02664</a><br>\nIn this paper, def 2.1, they define a \"weak pushout\" to be a pull back square which is initial amongst pullback squares that share the first two maps, as in the picture:<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/cPX_htaIxGugMcjf7lq6uk8S/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/cPX_htaIxGugMcjf7lq6uk8S/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/cPX_htaIxGugMcjf7lq6uk8S/image.png\"></a></div>",
        "id": 251487773,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1630460833
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is sorta funny to me. Has anybody seen a universal property like this before?</p>",
        "id": 251487791,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1630460857
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I've seen this elsewhere but for the same purpose, namely to have a version of pushout which still works and gives the expected thing when you work in a category whose maps are just the monomorphisms of some original category.</p>",
        "id": 254537210,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1632404677
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh wow really? Could you share the paper? Was it also in the realm of rep theory?</p>",
        "id": 254537622,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1632404816
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's definition 5.3 of <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1811.08014v3\">https://arxiv.org/abs/1811.08014v3</a> except I think the phrase \"pullback square\" (or square belonging to some chosen class of squares, which could be the pullback squares) is missing. But from context I believe that's what is intended.</p>",
        "id": 254539786,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1632405736
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks! I'll check it out.</p>",
        "id": 254542180,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1632406574
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Is this version of \"weak\" related to the <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/weak+colimit\">usual meaning</a> of weak (co)limits or are these orthogonal concepts?</p>",
        "id": 254545024,
        "sender_full_name": "Spencer Breiner",
        "timestamp": 1632407590
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think they're different. The one in the paper I posted is existence and uniqueness, but among a restricted class of diagrams.</p>",
        "id": 254545451,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1632407722
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I've been trying to think of a different name for this, but the best I've been able to come up with is a \"mushout\".</p>",
        "id": 254566716,
        "sender_full_name": "Spencer Breiner",
        "timestamp": 1632415624
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The paper I linked to calls it a \"restricted pushout\", which at least doesn't have another usage, as far as I know</p>",
        "id": 254569146,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1632416580
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This notion also comes up in a paper by Dyckerhoff-Kapranov on 'proto-exact categories' where there's an ambient (pointed) category that has coproducts, but they take a non-full subcategory which (among other things) loses the fold map A v A -&gt; A. So they also make such a modification</p>",
        "id": 254576435,
        "sender_full_name": "Ian Coley",
        "timestamp": 1632419541
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That might be the wrong citation, but it's definitely in a paper on proto-exact categories</p>",
        "id": 254576556,
        "sender_full_name": "Ian Coley",
        "timestamp": 1632419591
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276480\">Reid Barton</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/.22weak.20pushout.22.20universal.20among.20pullbacks/near/254537210\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I've seen this elsewhere but for the same purpose, namely to have a version of pushout which still works and gives the expected thing when you work in a category whose maps are just the monomorphisms of some original category.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>If I recall properly, this was the intention for introducing the \"proxy pushouts\" of Bumpus–Kocsis's <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2104.01841\">Spined categories: generalizing tree-width beyond graphs</a>, though there the solution looks different. I wonder if they're related at all.</p>",
        "id": 254616047,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1632436370
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I recently encountered a kind of dual version of this.<br>\nThe category Man of smooth manifolds and smooth maps doesn't have all pullbacks. But it does have pullbacks of submersions, and the pullback of a submersion is again a submersion. If we form the pullback of two submersions in Man, then we get a commutative square in the category Subm of smooth manifolds and submersions.<br>\nBut this square is not a pullback square in Subm, because the map into the pullback given by the universal property in Man might not be a submersion when the original maps are submersions. For example, the diagonal map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>M</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M \\to M \\times M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.76666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> is never a submersion if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> has positive dimension.</p>\n<p>Is there some way to characterize these squares in Subm (squares that are pullbacks in Man) purely in terms of Subm? Note that dualizing the condition that started this thread doesn't work--a pullback of submersions doesn't have to be a pushout, for example if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\to Z</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y \\to Z</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span></span></span></span> have disjoint images which together do not make up all of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Z</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 260812200,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1636470919
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Alternatively, I wonder what kind of axiomatization of these \"proxy pullbacks\" would make sense (note for example they still satisfy the pullback pasting and cancellation laws, inherited from Man).</p>",
        "id": 260812424,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1636471002
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The condition in the paper <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276092\">@Nathanael Arkor</span> linked to is interesting, the existence and uniqueness of a morphism comparing two \"proxy pullbacks\" over the same base--I think that's satisfied in this Subm example.</p>",
        "id": 260812695,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1636471104
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276480\">Reid Barton</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/.22weak.20pushout.22.20universal.20among.20pullbacks/near/260812424\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Alternatively, I wonder what kind of axiomatization of these \"proxy pullbacks\" would make sense (note for example they still satisfy the pullback pasting and cancellation laws, inherited from Man).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This conjures up a nice idea of being able to embed a given category equipped with proxy pullbacks faithfully into another category such that those squares become pullbacks</p>",
        "id": 260814211,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1636471634
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Besides the pasting property, you can observe that these are \"sub-pullback squares\", in the sense that given <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><msub><mi>M</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>→</mo><mi>N</mi><mo>←</mo><msub><mi>M</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>:</mo><mi>g</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f: M_1 \\rightarrow N \\leftarrow M_2 : g</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.10903em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">←</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.10903em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span></span></span></span> there is an injective function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>u</mi><mi>b</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><msub><mi>M</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mo>×</mo><mi>N</mi></msub><msub><mi>M</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>↪</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msup><mi>g</mi><mo mathvariant=\"normal\" lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">′</mo></msup><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><msup><mi>f</mi><mo mathvariant=\"normal\" lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">′</mo></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>∈</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>u</mi><mi>b</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><msub><mi>M</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>×</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>u</mi><mi>b</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><msub><mi>M</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>∣</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>∘</mo><msup><mi>g</mi><mo mathvariant=\"normal\" lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">′</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>∘</mo><msup><mi>f</mi><mo mathvariant=\"normal\" lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">′</mo></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Hom}_{Subm}(X,M_1 \\times_N M_2) \\hookrightarrow \\{ (g&#x27;,f&#x27;) \\in \\mathrm{Hom}_{Subm}(X,M_1)  \\times  \\mathrm{Hom}_{Subm}(X,M_2) \\mid f \\circ g&#x27; = g \\circ f&#x27; \\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Hom</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.33610799999999996em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">u</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">bm</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.10903em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\"><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.32833099999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-